codex
Four closure paths are structurally sound in the implementation: cross-account endpoint takeover is atomically rejected; queued reads recheck identity before cache/return boundaries; revoke/regrant advances both local and server epochs while quarantining old work; and production writers bind captured identity/epoch headers.

One database authorization gap remains under review: the older migration still grants authenticated users direct `INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE` on `push_subscriptions`, which bypasses the new farm/access-epoch RPC fence. I’m confirming its reachability and whether any later migration revokes it.
The notification flow and four core closure implementations are traced. A direct-table privilege appears to bypass the new push-subscription epoch RPC, so verification is focused on proving that gap and the tests’ coverage of it.
